<h1 class="hero-h">AI Implementation: Partner vs Internal Team <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">Most teams should do both — sequentially.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Should you bring in an outside AI implementation partner or build the capability internally? At $5M-$50M B2B, the right answer is usually 'both, sequentially' — partner first to compress time-to-value, internal capability built during and after. Here's the decision framework.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Partner first for the first 1-3 workflows; build internal capability during the engagement; transition to internal ownership at 90-180 days. Trying to start internally usually wastes 60-120 days on trial-and-error that a partner would compress. Trying to outsource everything indefinitely usually wastes money and creates dependency.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">When to start with a partner</h2><ul class="ul"><li>You haven't successfully shipped an AI workflow in production yet.</li><li>Your internal team doesn't have someone who has done this before.</li><li>You need rollout faster than internal trial-and-error allows (typical: 90 days with partner vs 6 months without).</li><li>You want to compress the political work — outside voice can move what internal politics blocks.</li><li>Budget allows \$5K-\$50K for fixed-fee implementation engagement.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">When to start internally (no partner)</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Someone on your team has shipped AI workflows at a previous company.</li><li>You have 4-6 months of patience for trial-and-error.</li><li>Budget is too tight for any outside help.</li><li>You're at <20 people and the founder can do this themselves.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">The hybrid approach (most common right answer)</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Months 0-3:</strong> Partner-led implementation. Partner ships 1-3 workflows; trains the named internal owner alongside.</li><li><strong>Months 3-6:</strong> Joint operation. Partner advises; internal owner runs day-to-day. Partner present for major decisions.</li><li><strong>Months 6-12:</strong> Internal ownership. Partner on call for new initiatives. Quarterly check-ins.</li><li><strong>Months 12+:</strong> Fully internal unless major new initiative.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Cost comparison</h2><p class="body">The math usually favors the hybrid: partner compresses time-to-value, internal capability ensures sustainability.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Common mistakes</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Hiring the partner without naming the internal owner.</strong> When the partner leaves, knowledge leaves with them.</li><li><strong>Letting the partner do everything.</strong> Internal capability must be built during the engagement, not after.</li><li><strong>Cutting partner short before transition is complete.</strong> Saves a month of fees; loses 6 months of compounding outcomes.</li><li><strong>Extending the partner indefinitely.</strong> If you're still using the partner at 18 months, ownership has not transferred.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">How to structure the partnership for handoff</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Name the internal owner at engagement kickoff.</li><li>Internal owner attends every partner working session.</li><li>All Projects, prompts, and documentation lives in your systems (not the partner's).</li><li>Define handoff milestones in the engagement letter ("by week 8, internal owner runs workflow #1 solo").</li><li>Plan a clean exit date with quarterly check-in retainer after.</li></ul></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How do I evaluate AI implementation partners?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Reference checks with similar clients; demand to see real deliverables from past engagements; ask about their handoff process.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can we hire a dedicated internal AI engineer instead?</h3><p class="faq-qa">At <50 people, usually no — not enough work to justify. At 100+, sometimes.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should we hire the partner's lead consultant as a full-time employee?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Sometimes works. Have the conversation openly; partners with high turnover view this as normal.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">What's the right partner profile for our size?</h3><p class="faq-qa">B2B at \$5M-\$30M: small specialized firm (under 10 people). Larger orgs: mid-sized practice. Avoid Big-4 unless you specifically need the brand.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can the partner help with hiring our internal AI lead?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes — good partners help spec and source the eventual full-time hire as part of the handoff plan.</p></div>
</div></section>

